@node oMulU64L "OpenUtil.library / Math Functions / oMulU64L()"

  NAME
        oMulU64L -- Multiply two 64-Bit numbers

  SYNOPSIS
        oMulU64L (SrcHi, SrcLo, DestHi, DestLo)
                    D0     D1     A0      A1

        long oMulU64L (ULONG, ULONG, ULONG *, ULONG *)

  FUNCTION
        This function multiplies two 64-Bit values.

  INPUTS
        SrcHi    - The upper 32 bits of the source value

        SrcLo    - The lower 32 bits of the source value

        DestHi   - A pointer to a ULONG which holds the upper 32 bits of
                   the second value and which will receive the upper 32 bits
                   of the result value.

        DestLo   - A pointer to a ULONG which holds the lower 32 bits of
                   the second value and which will receive the lower 32 bits
                   of the result value.

  RESULT
        Success    BOOL. If TRUE, DestHi & DestLo will contain the result of
                   the multiplication, FALSE indicates a 64-bit overflow error.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oDivU64L() " link "oDivU64L"}, @{" oAddU64() " link "oAddU64"}@{" oSubU64() " link "oSubU64"}
@endnode
@node oNum64Comp "OpenUtil.library / Math Functions / oNum64Comp()"

  NAME
        oNum64Comp -- Compare two 64-Bit numbers

  SYNOPSIS
        oNum64Comp (SrcHi, SrcLo, DestHi, DestLo)
                     D0      D1     D2      D3

        long oNum64Comp (ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG)

  FUNCTION
        This function compares two (unsigned) 64-Bit numbers

  INPUTS
        SrcHi       - The upper 32 bits of the first value

        SrcLo       - The lower 32 bits of the first value

        DestHi      - The upper 32 bits of the second value

        DestLo      - The lower 32 bits of the second value

  RESULT
        long          0 if both numbers are equal
                      1 if Src is higher than Dest
                     -1 if Src is lower than Dest
  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oNum64ToStr "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oNum64ToStr()"

  NAME
        oNum64ToStr -- convert a 64-bit value to a decimal string

  SYNOPSIS
        oNum64ToStr (ValueHi, ValueLo, Buffer, BufSize, Flags)
                       D0        D1      A0       D2      D3

        long oNum64ToStr (ULONG, ULONG, STRPTR, ULONG, ULONG)

  FUNCTION
        This function converts a 64-bit numeric value to a decimal string.
        oNum64ToStr() is compatible to @{"oNumToStr()" link oNumToStr}, except that the
        value to convert consists of two longwords, and hex or binary
        conversion is not included since 64-bit hex/binary strings may be
        created by two @{"oNumToStr()" link oNumToStr} calls.

  INPUTS
        ValueHi - The upper 32 bits of the value to convert

        ValueLo - The lower 32 bits of the value to convert

        Buffer  - An output string buffer for the converted string.

        BufSize - The maximum output buffer size.
                  If BufSize is NULL, OpenUtil.library assumes that the output
                  buffer is big enough anyway. Refer to "Table Of Buffer
                  Sizes" to see how big the destination string buffer should
                  be. The maximum needed buffer size is 29 bytes including
                  the trailing NULL byte.
                  If the output string doesn't fit into the Buffer, RESULT
                  will be -1 and the output buffer won't get touched anyway.
                  It's up to you about what to do if the string doesn't fit
                  into the buffer, e.g. using strings like ">1 Bio." or such.

        Flags   - Options as follows. All flags have the same names as the
                  ones used for @{"oNumToStr()" link oNumToStr}.

        oNTSF_LEADINGZEROES - Output string with leading zeroes. This option
                              overrides the text formatting flags.

        oNTSF_LEADINGSIGN   - Add a leading arithmetic symbol ("#").
                              This symbol is added as a prefix, placed directly
                              left of the leftmost digit.
                              Remember that this option raises the needed output
                              buffer size. See "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_RIGHTFORMAT   - String gets right-formatted. The number of
                              leading spaces depends on the buffer size used.
                              Refer to "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_LEFTFORMAT    - Buffer gets filled up with spaces behind the
                              numeric string. Refer to "Table Of Buffer
                              Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_CENTERFORMAT  - The numeric string gets centered inside the
                              output buffer. Refer to "Table Of Buffer Sizes"
                              below.

        oNTSF_TENDLEFT      - This flag works together with oNTSF_CENTERFORMAT.
                              Normally, this function tends to place the center
                              formatted strings a bit more right, because half
                              space chars cannot be printed. With this flag you
                              may change this behaviour to put the strings more
                              left.

        oNTSF_GROUPING      - Add group separators to the string.
                              Example: Output "42658313" as "42,658,313".
                              Remember that this option raises the needed output
                              buffer size. See "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_NUMLOCALE     - If the oNTSF_GROUPING flag is set, with this option
                              the current Locale numeric group separator is used
                              instead of the default group separator char.

        oNTSF_MONLOCALE     - If the oNTSF_GROUPING flag is set, with this Flag
                              the current Locale monetary group separator is
                              used instead of the default group separator char.

        oNTSF_SIGNED        - Interpret Value as signed number. BufSize always
                              raises by one additional byte. Negative numbers
                              get a "-" prefix, positive ones get a " " prefix.

        oNTSF_PLUSSIGN      - If oNTSF_SIGNED is set, positive numbers get a "+"
                              sign added, instead of the default " " char.

        oNTSF_SWAPSIGNS     - If both oNTSF_SIGNED and oNTSF_LEADINGSIGN flags
                              are set, this option swaps the two chars from
                              "-#" to "#-".

  RESULT
        Result  - NULL if everything went ok, or -1 if the string didn't fit
                  into the buffer (this error may only occur if BufSize was
                  non-zero).

  NOTES
        Same rules as with @{"oNumToStr()" link oNumToStr}.


        Table Of Buffer Sizes
        ---------------------

        The following table shows up the minimum output buffer sizes needed
        to convert any Value without the event of a buffer overflow.
        This is useful if you want position-formatted strings.

        All buffer sizes include the trailing NULL byte.

        Type  | Pure | With Leading Symbol | With Separators | With Both
        ------+------+---------------------+-----------------+----------
         LONG |  22  |          23         |       28        |    29
        ULONG |  21  |          22         |       27        |    28
        ----------------------------------------------------------------

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oNumToStr() " link oNumToStr}, @{" oStrTo64() " link "oStrTo64"}, @{" oAtol() " link "oAtol"}
@endnode
@node oNumToStr "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oNumToStr()"

  NAME
        oNumToStr -- convert a numeric value to a string

  SYNOPSIS
        oNumToStr (Value, Buffer, BufSize, Flags)
                    D0      A0       D1      D2

        long oNumToStr (ULONG, STRPTR, ULONG, STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        This function converts a numeric value to either a decimal, hex,
        or binary string. This function is useful in situations where a
        standalone AmigaOS FormatString isn't flexible enough.

  INPUTS
        Value   - The numeric value to convert.

        Buffer  - An output string buffer for the converted string.

        BufSize - The maximum output buffer size. The string terminator (null-
                  byte) counts. If BufSize is set to NULL, OpenUtil.library
                  assumes that the output buffer is big enough anyway. Refer
                  to "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below to see how many bytes are
                  needed. If the output string doesn't fit into the Buffer,
                  Result will be -1 and the output buffer stays untouched.

        Flags   - Options as follows:
                  (same usage as, for example, the exec memory attributes)

        oNTSF_HEX           - Convert Value to hex string (default: decimal)

        oNTSF_BIN           - Convert Value to binary string (default: decimal)

        oNTSF_WORD          - Value has WORD size (default: LONG)

        oNTSF_BYTE          - Value has BYTE size (default: LONG)

        oNTSF_LEADINGZEROES - Output string with leading zeroes. Of course,
                              this option overrides the text formatting flags.

        oNTSF_LEADINGSIGN   - Add a leading arithmetic symbol, depending
                              on the stated numeric system:
                              - Decimal strings get a "#" prefix
                              - Hex strings get a "$" prefix
                              - Binary strings get a "%" prefix
                              The prefix is always placed directly left of the
                              leftmost digit.
                              Remember that this option raises the needed output
                              buffer size. See "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_RIGHTFORMAT   - String gets right-formatted. The number of
                              leading spaces depends on the numeric system,
                              the Value size (BYTE/WORD/LONG) and the buffer
                              size. Refer to "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_LEFTFORMAT    - Buffer gets filled up with spaces behind the
                              numeric string. Refer to "Table Of Buffer
                              Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_CENTERFORMAT  - The numeric string gets centered inside the
                              output buffer. Refer to "Table Of Buffer Sizes"
                              below.

        oNTSF_TENDLEFT      - This flag works together with oNTSF_CENTERFORMAT.
                              Normally, this function tends to place the center
                              formatted strings a bit more right, because half
                              space chars cannot be printed. With this flag you
                              may change this behaviour to put the strings more
                              left.

        oNTSF_LOWERCASE     - Output hex chars in lower case

        oNTSF_GROUPING      - Add group separators to the string. Example:
                              Output (decimal) "42658313" as "42,658,313".
                              Remember that this option raises the needed output
                              buffer size. See "Table Of Buffer Sizes" below.

        oNTSF_NUMLOCALE     - If the oNTSF_GROUPING flag is set, with this option
                              the current Locale numeric group separator is used
                              instead of the default group separator char.
                              This option only affects decimal strings.

        oNTSF_MONLOCALE     - If the oNTSF_GROUPING flag is set, with this Flag
                              the current Locale monetary group separator is
                              used instead of the default group separator char.
                              This option only affects decimal strings.

        oNTSF_SIGNED        - Interpret Value as signed number. BufSize always
                              raises by one additional byte. Negative numbers
                              get a "-" prefix, positive ones get a " " prefix.

        oNTSF_PLUSSIGN      - If oNTSF_SIGNED is set, positive numbers get a "+"
                              sign added, instead of the default " " char.

        oNTSF_SWAPSIGNS     - If both oNTSF_SIGNED and oNTSF_LEADINGSIGN flags are
                              set, this option swaps the two chars from (e.g.)
                              "-$" to "$-".

  RESULT
        Result  - NULL if everything went ok, or -1 if the string didn't fit
                  into the buffer (this error may only occur if BufSize was
                  non-zero).

  NOTES
        Do *not* use undefined flags or senseless flag combinations.
        For example, don't use oNTSF_WORD together with oNTSF_BYTE.

        Formatting and leading zeroes: the number of spaces/zeroes depends
        on the given BufSize, but the whole string is never longer than the
        maximum needed number of chars. If you convert a decimal WORD value
        using a BufSize of 500 bytes, the string will only contain 5 digits,
        zeroes or spaces plus optional arithmetic sign and group separator,
        because the result cannot have more than 5 digits (the highest word
        value is 65535).

        Grouping: beyond the group separator chars, other Locale Grouping
        preferences are ignored in order to keep the used buffer sizes fixed.
        Groups of decimal characters are always 3 chars in size. Groups are
        separated from the rightmost digit to the left side, e.g. "37,653",
        "1,956,221" or "281,344".
        Hex strings get split into two equal groups.
        Binary numbers get split into groups of 8 chars.
        However, strings of BYTE size never contain any group separators,
        no matter which numeric system is used.
        Default group separarator for decimal strings is the "," char.
        For hexadecimal, a Space character (" ") is used; and the dot (".")
        is used with binary.
        the oNTSF_USExxxLOCALE flags have no effect with hex or binary strings.


        Table Of Buffer Sizes
        ---------------------

        The following table shows up the minimum output buffer sizes needed
        to convert any Value without the event of a buffer overflow.

        All buffer sizes include the trailing NULL byte.

        String type  | Pure | With Leading Symbol | With Separators | With Both
        -------------+------+---------------------+-----------------+----------
        Decimal LONG |  11  |         12          |       14        |    15
               ULONG |  12  |         13          |       15        |    16
                WORD |   6  |          7          |        7        |     8
               UWORD |   7  |          8          |        8        |     9
                BYTE |   4  |          5          |        4        |     5
               UBYTE |   5  |          6          |        5        |     6
        -------------+------+---------------------+-----------------+----------
        Hex     LONG |   9  |         10          |       10        |    11
               ULONG |  10  |         11          |       11        |    12
                WORD |   5  |          6          |        6        |     7
               UWORD |   6  |          7          |        7        |     8
                BYTE |   3  |          4          |        3        |     4
               UBYTE |   4  |          5          |        4        |     5
        -------------+------+---------------------+----------------------------
        Binary  LONG |  33  |         34          |       36        |    37
               ULONG |  33  |         34          |       36        |    37
                WORD |  17  |         18          |       18        |    19
               UWORD |  17  |         18          |       18        |    19
                BYTE |   9  |         10          |        9        |    10
               UBYTE |   9  |         10          |        9        |    10
        -----------------------------------------------------------------------

        Signed binary numbers don't need an additional byte, because the
        highest bit doesn't need to get displayed anymore; if you pass 255 as
        Value and oNTSF_BINARY and oNTSF_SIGNED as Flags, you'll get "-0000001"
        as result, instead of "11111111". Signed binary is rarely used..

        This function description is more complex than the function itself.
        I only suggest to try it out. Try several values in hex, binary
        or decimal format, and do not use any additional flags first.
        Then add some flags and look what happens.

        In general, it may be helpful to know that "BufSize" is just a little
        bonus for easy text formatting. Let's have an example: we want to
        convert several (unknown) decimal values, which are always inside a
        range from 0 to 99999, and you want all output strings right-formatted,
        written into a box (or gadget) of 5 chars width. You'll have to use
        LONG conversion because 99999 is larger than a WORD. Now the library
        function will always insert *at least* five zeroes or spaces on the
        left side of the string, due to the fact that LONGs may have up to 10
        decimal digits. This is too much for our gadget. We you can limit BufSize
        to 5 + null byte = 6 bytes, and the problem is solved. If we do so, note
        that values larger than 99999 will cause a buffer overflow error.

        In most cases, simply setting BufSize to NULL while using a buffer of
        at least 37 bytes is a practical method, especially if the new numeric
        string gets embedded into an AmigaDOS format string using %s.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oNum64ToStr() " link oNum64ToStr}, @{" oAtol() " link "oAtol"}
@endnode
@node oOpenMsgWaitA "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oOpenMsgWaitA()"

  NAME
        oOpenMsgWaitA   -- Open a Window containing a progress information
                           text and a Status Bar to display the current
                           operation progress.
        oOpenMsgWait    -- varargs stub for oOpenMsgWaitA()

  SYNOPSIS
        oOpenMsgWaitA (TitleText, BodyText, GadgetText, MaxValue, Argv)
                          A0         A1         A2         D0      A3

        oOpenMsgWait  (TitleText, BodyText, MaxValue, ...)

        struct oMsgWait * oOpenMsgWaitA (STRPTR, STRPTR, ULONG, long *)

        struct oMsgWait * oOpenMsgWait  (STRPTR, STRPTR, ULONG, ...)

  FUNCTION
        Open a Window for imaging an operation progress indicator, containing
        Title & Body texts, a Status Bar and optional some user interaction.

  INPUTS
        TitleText       - The Window Title text.

        BodyText        - Window body text. The overall length of BodyText
                          @{B}after@{ub} RawDoFmt() is limited to 4096 Bytes.

        GadgetText      - A string for an interaction Gadget which is normally
                          used to abort the progress. If you pass a string here,
                          a button-kind Gadget gets attached, labeled with the
                          passed string. You may use '_' as underscore char for
                          a HotKey which gets used for the button then.
                          In addition, a Window Close Gadget gets attached.

                          IDCMP messaging is handled by @{"oUpdateMsgWait()" link "oUpdateMsgWait"}.

                          If you pass NULL here, IDCMP messaging is turned off.
                          The action gadget is not drawn and the Window also
                          hasn't got a Window Close Gadget.

        MaxValue          The maximum Value where the Status Bar gets fully drawn,
                          which equals 100% completed. For example, if you're
                          going to add 157 files to a compressed archive, you
                          may prefer setting MaxValue to 157 instead of the
                          default value of 100 (which draws the Status Bar
                          according to percentage values).

                          Note that very small values (example: 5) will cause
                          the Status Bar to grow block-wise instead of scrolling
                          smoothly up to full size.

        Argv            - RawDoFmt() args for BodyText.

  RESULT
        MsgWait         - An oMsgWait structure containing all needed information
                          or NULL (out of memory or unable to open Window).

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oCloseMsgWait() " link "oCloseMsgWait"}, @{" oUpdateMsgWait() " link "oUpdateMsgWait"},
        @{" oCreateStatusBarA() " link "oCreateStatusBarA"},
@endnode
@node oRandom "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oRandom()"

  NAME
        oRandom -- Generate a random number

  SYNOPSIS
        oRandom (RndSeed, MinValue, MaxValue)
                   A0        D0        D1

        long oRandom (struct oRndSeed *, long, long)

  FUNCTION
        This function returns a (pseudo) random number. The System Clock can
        be attached to take influence. Refer to the @{"oCreateRndSeed()" link "oCreateRndSeed"} description
        for further details.

  INPUTS
        RndSeed    - An oRndSeed structure, which must be allocated first using
                     @{"oCreateRndSeed()" link "oCreateRndSeed"}.

        MinValue   - The minimum value for the random number.

        MaxValue   - The maximum value for the random number.

  RESULT
        Random     - A random number inside the passed boundaries.

  EXAMPLE

        C:
           // an amazing Dice Booth game with complete GUI and multiple dices :)

              ULONG   PlayerScore;

              struct oRndSeed * RndSeed;

              if (RndSeed = oCreateRndSeed(0))
              {
                do
                {
                  PlayerScore = oRandom(RndSeed,1,6)
                              + oRandom(RndSeed,1,6)
                              + oRandom(RndSeed,1,6);

                  if (PlayerScore == 3 * 6)
                  {
                    oMsgInfo("Congratulations","You just have won an eel !");
                  }
                  else
                  {
                    oMsgInfo("Not Enough",
                             "Only %ld. Better luck next time..",
                             PlayerScore);
                  }
                } while(oMsgYesNo("Game Over","Throw again ?"));

                oDeleteRndSeed(RndSeed);
              }

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oCreateRndSeed() " link "oCreateRndSeed"}, @{" oDeleteRndSeed() " link "oDeleteRndSeed"}
@endnode
@node oRemExecHeader "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oRemExecHeader()"

  NAME
        oRemExecHeader   -- Remove & free an Exec List Header

  SYNOPSIS
        oRemExecHeader (Base)
                         A0

        struct Node * oRemExecHeader (struct List *)

  FUNCTION
        This function frees an Exec List Header back to memory.
        
  INPUTS
        Base       - An Exec List Header which must have been allocated using
                     @{"oAllocVecPooledA()" link "oAllocVecPooledA"} or any
                     other OpenUtil function, like @{"oCreateList()" link "oCreateList"}.
  RESULT
        Node       - If the passed List wasn't empty, oRemExecHeader() returns
                     the Node chain which was linked to the List Header, null-
                     terminated at both sides. If the List was empty, Result
                     will be NULL.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oAddExecHeader() " link "oAddExecHeader"}, @{" oDeleteList() " link "oDeleteList"}
@endnode
@node oRequestLib "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oRequestLib()"

  NAME
        oRequestLib -- Request a Library or Device using a selection Requester

  SYNOPSIS
        oRequestLib (TitleText, DefaultName, Type, Buffer)
                        A0           A1       D0     A2

        long oRequestLib (STRPTR, STRPTR, long, STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        This function opens a Requester for choosing one of the Libraries
        (or Devices) currently in memory or installed in LIBS: (or DEVS:).

  INPUTS
        TitleText       - The Window title string or NULL, where a default
                          string is used instead.

        DefaultName     - A default library/device name, without path.
                          If the passed string matches a Library/Device in the
                          List, it gets marked as default choice. May be NULL.

        Type            - NT_LIBRARY (select a Library) or
                          NT_DEVICE  (select a Device)

        Buffer          - A string buffer for receiving the name of the
                          requested Library or Device (case-exact name without
                          path). The Buffer size must be at least 31 bytes.

  RESULT
        long            NULL if the user has selected a valid Library / Device,
                             where the passed Buffer contains the name of the
                             choosen object,

                           1 if the user has canceled the Requester, or

                          -1 if the function failed to open the Requester.

  BUGS
        This function scans the Exec Base Device & Lib Lists; this will conflict
        with future AmigaOS versions, but there is currently no other way.
        Version Numbers higher than 127 are not supported because OpenLibrary()
        treats the passed Version number as signed BYTE even if rt_Version is
        defined as UBYTE, while lib_Version is defined as UWORD..

        Beyond that, i found no way to safely get the LibRevision numbers from
        disk located libaries, because many Libs & Devs i found on my harddisk
        do strange things with the standard Exec RomTag structure. Some set the
        RTF_AUTOINIT flag but set the RT_INIT pointer to NULL, others let the
        InitStruct stream begin with an END command. As i now tried to parse
        the Library IDString for getting the Revision number, i often found
        the wildest things completely different from the exactly defined syntax:
        "Name Version.Revision (Date)". Some just don't include a revision number.
        The only way to get a Library Revison Number is to open it using
        OpenLibrary(), or at least to initialize it with MakeLibrary(), but who
        knows what some unknown Library does when initializing: allocating
        tons of things, opening Windows or whatever. So this function only
        displays Version but *no* Revision numbers, because i simply have
        enough. Let's see if future AmigaOS releases kick ass or not.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oRTrim "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oRTrim()"

  NAME
        oRTrim     -- Strip trailing TAB and SPACE chars from a string

  SYNOPSIS
        oRTrim (String)
                  A0

        STRPTR oRTrim (STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        This function removes all TAB and SPACE characters from the right side
        of a given string.

  INPUTS
        String     - The string to trim

  RESULT
        String     - The modified string (equal to input)

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oLTrim() " link "oLTrim"}, @{" oAllTrim() " link "oAllTrim"}
@endnode
@node oSearchRecordA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oSearchRecordA()"

  NAME
        oSearchRecordA -- Search a record (Node) in a List
        oSearchRecord  -- varargs stub for oSearchRecordA()

  SYNOPSIS
        oSearchRecordA (Base, Offset, Mode, Subject, Tags)
                         A0     D0     D1     D2      A1

        oSearchRecord  (Base, Offset, Mode, Subject, FirstTag, ...)

        struct Node * oSearchRecordA (struct List *, long, ULONG, APTR, struct TagItem *)

        struct Node * oSearchRecord  (struct List *, long, ULONG, APTR, Tag, ...)

  FUNCTION
        This function searches for a Node in an Exec List. You may search
        for strings or binary data at any offset.

  INPUTS
        Base          - An Exec List (may be empty).

        Offset        - The offset in each List Node where the search data
                        is located

        Mode          - The desired search mode; one of:

                        oMATCHMODE_Byte

                          - Search for a BYTE value passed in ti_Data (as ULONG)

                        oMATCHMODE_Word

                          - Search for a WORD value passed in ti_Data (as ULONG)

                        oMATCHMODE_Long

                          - Search for a LONG value passed in ti_Data

                        oMATCHMODE_QuadPtr

                          - Search for a QUADWORD value (64-bit number). Since
                            ti_Data can't hold the two ULONGs, oSearchRecordA()
                            awaits a pointer to a pair of ULONGs where the first
                            one holds the upper 32 bits and the second holds the
                            lower 32 bits.

                        oMATCHMODE_StrBegin

                          - Search for a string entry which begins with the
                            search string passed in ti_Data (STRPTR).
                            Useful for things like auto key name completion
                            (TAB-completion etc.) in ListViews.

                        oMATCHMODE_StrEnd

                          - Search for a string entry which ends with the
                            search string passed in ti_Data (STRPTR).

                        oMATCHMODE_StrAny

                          - Search for a string entry which contains the
                            search string passed in ti_Data (STRPTR) at
                            any position.

                        oMATCHMODE_StrExact

                          - Search for a string entry which is exactly equal to
                            the search string passed in ti_Data (STRPTR).
                            "Exact" doesn't include case-sensitivity, which is
                            controlled by a Tag defined below.

                        oMATCHMODE_StrPattern

                          - Search for an AmigaDOS Pattern match. This Mode
                            requires at least 2000 bytes Stack space. Since
                            OpenUtil.library sets the RNF_WILDSTAR flag at
                            startup, you can always use the asterisk ("*")
                            as wildstar character as long as OpenUtil.library
                            is opened.

        Subject       - What to search for. This one is defined as APTR, but
                        can be either UBYTE/UWORD/ULONG for binary, ULONG *
                        for QUADWORDs or STRPTR for Strings. C programmers
                        will need type casting.

        Tags          - Optional. The following Tags are supported:

                        oSR_CaseSensitive

                          - BOOL. If TRUE, string search will be case-sensitive
                            instead of the default (FALSE).

                        oSR_Pointer

                          - ULONG. The value you pass in ti_Data states how
                            many pointer down references are performed at the
                            specified offset. Only used in special cases,
                            this one is best explained in the @{"oSortListA()" link "oSortListA"}
                            description and @{"example" link "CXoSortListA"}.

                        oSR_StartNode

                          - (struct Node *). The passed Node is used as start
                            point where to begin the search. Must be part of
                            the passed List or NULL; in this case the first
                            Node is used (Top or Bottom, depending on search
                            direction).

                        oSR_Exclusive

                          - BOOL. Only used together with oSR_StartNode.
                            This Tag excludes the passed Start Node. The
                            search will start at the following Node (if there
                            is any). After a match is returned, you may pass
                            the returned Node with oSR_StartNode while using
                            oSR_Exclusive to search for further matches
                            behind that Node.

                        oSR_Up

                          - BOOL. This will search from the bottom to the top
                            of the List. If a StartNode is passed, searching
                            goes from that Node in upward direction.
                            Default: FALSE.

  RESULT
        Node            - The first Record (Node) which matches the search
                          conditions or NULL if the end of the List was
                          reached without a match.

                          When using oMATCHMODE_StrPattern, note that
                          oSearchRecordA() calls dos.library/MatchPattern(),
                          which checks for Stack overflows. If oSearchRecordA()
                          returns FALSE, check IoErr(), which may be NULL (okay
                          but no match) or (for example) ERROR_TOO_MANY_LEVELS.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
  SEE ALSO
        @{" oGetRecord() " link "oGetRecord"}, @{" oGetRecordNumber() " link "oGetRecordNumber"}
@endnode
@node oSetFileExtension "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oSetFileExtension()"

  NAME
        oSetFileExtension -- Add or replace a file name extension

  SYNOPSIS
        oSetFileExtension (FileName, Extension, Buffer, BufSize, Flags)
                              A0         A1       A2      D0       D1

        long oSetFileExtension (STRPTR, STRPTR, STRPTR, long, ULONG)

  FUNCTION
        This function adds a file extension string to a given file name.
        By default (without any Flags set), the new file extension gets added
        at the end of FileName, including a leading extension dot.

        Example: "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.IFF.lha" gets converted to

                 "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.IFF.lha.NewExtension"

  INPUTS
        FileName      - An AmigaDOS file name, with or without path

        Extension     - A file extension which to add to the end of FileName.
                        This extension string is passed without a leading dot
                        char. For example, pass "IFF" instead of ".IFF".

        Buffer        - A destination buffer where the new name gets copied to.

        BufSize       - Size of the passed Buffer. A size of 256 Bytes is always
                        big enough and won't return an error.

        Flags         - oSFEF_REPLACELAST

                          - Replace the last file extension found in FileName.
                            Example: "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.IFF.lha" gets converted to
                                     "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.IFF.NewExtension"

                      - oSFEF_REPLACEALL

                          - If FileName contains multiple extensions, this one
                            will replace the old file extension(s) at the first
                            extension position in FileName (not the path part).
                            Example: "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.IFF.lha" gets converted to
                                     "DH1:Pics.256/MyPic.NewExtension"

                      - oSFEF_RENAME

                          - Rename the file on disk. This will rename FileName
                            to the new name written to Buffer. If this flag
                            isn't set, only the new string is constructed.

  RESULT
        Success       BOOL. If FALSE, something went wrong. Use IoErr() to get
                      an error code. This function may fail if the passed Buffer
                      is too small, the passed file extension is too long ( >29
                      chars), the new FileName (including path) is longer than
                      255 chars or if the function failed to rename the file.

  EXAMPLE

        C:
                char FileName[256];
                char Buffer  [256];

                long AllRight = FALSE;

                oStrCopy("DH1:MonthsOfWork/MyBestPic.IFF",&FileName[0]);

                // Now going to rename an existing file by adding a ".bak"
                // extension before writing the new file. After successful
                // saving, the old backup file gets deleted.

                if (oSetFileExtension(&FileName[0],
                                      "bak",
                                      &Buffer[0],
                                      256,
                                      oSFEF_RENAME))
                {
                  if (MySavePicture(&FileName[0]))
                  {
                    if (!(DeleteFile(&Buffer[0])))
                    {
                      oMsgFault("Cleanup problem","Can't delete the safety backup file:");
                    }
                    AllRight = TRUE;
                  }
                }

                if (!AllRight)
                {
                  oMsgFault(0,"Can't save picture:");
                }

  NOTES
        If the file part of the new FileName (written to Buffer) gets longer
        than 30 chars, oSetFileExtension() truncates the file part to a maximum
        length of 30 chars by shifting the new extension in left direction.
        If Result is TRUE, Buffer will always contain a file name with a file
        part of max. 30 chars length. oSetFileExtension() doesn't check if
        FileName or Extension contain characters which are illegal for use with
        AmigaDOS path & file names.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oSetTagData "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oSetTagData()"

  NAME
        oSetTagData      -- Set a Tag data value (the pendant to GetTagData())

  SYNOPSIS
        oSetTagData (TagValue, TagData, Tags)
                        D0        D1     A0

        ULONG oSetTagData (ULONG, ULONG, struct TagItem *)

  FUNCTION
        Searches for a Tag in the passed TagList. If found, Tag->ti_Data
        gets set to the passed TagData value. Handy for re-using Tags.

  INPUTS
        TagValue        - ID value of the Tag to search and set.

        TagData         - The value to set Tag.ti_Data with.

        Tags            - TagList. May be NULL.

  RESULT
        Success           BOOL. If FALSE, Tags or TagValue was NULL or
                          the specified Tag wasn't found.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oSortListA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oSortListA()"

  NAME
        oSortListA       -- Sort Exec Lists by contents
        oSortList        -- varargs stub for oSortListA()

  SYNOPSIS
        oSortListA (Base, Offset, Mode, Tags)
                    A0     D0     D1    A1

        oSortList  (Base, Offset, Mode, FirstTag, ...)

        struct List * oSortListA (struct List *, long, long, struct TagItem *)

        struct List * oSortList  (struct List *, long, long, Tag, ...)

  FUNCTION
        oSortListA() is a flexible List sort function using a Bucket-Sort
        algorythm, implemented in highly optimized Assembler. This provides
        maximum sort speed, because it always uses *linear* time, which means
        that nothing (yet) can beat it.

        Beyond that, Bucket-Sort is of type STABLE, which means that the
        original sort order stays intact (as secondary order) after sorting.
        For example, sorting a person List by first names and then sorting
        again by last names always puts Albert Smith before Zelda Smith.

  INPUTS
        Base            - An Exec List (may be empty).

        Offset          - Offset in each record (Node) where to compare data.
                          Must not be negative, else nothing happens.
                          See example below.

        Mode            - one of:

                          oSORTMODE_STRING   - Sort by strings.

                          oSORTMODE_BYTE     - Sort by byte values.

                          oSORTMODE_WORD     - Sort by word values.

                          oSORTMODE_LONG     - Sort by long values.

                          oSORTMODE_QUAD     - Sort by quad-word values (64-Bit)
                                               (or just XL - Extra Long :^)

                          oSortListA() aborts when Mode is unknown.

        Tags            - optional (else pass NULL):

                          oSL_PADOUT

                            BOOL. Only for sorting strings, which need to get
                            padded out with null-bytes up to full string length,
                            else List may get sorted wrong. If you're not sure if
                            you've always got fully cleared string buffers everytime
                            a string is copied to, oSL_PADOUT will do the work for
                            you. Ignored if oSORTMODE_STRING isn't used. In most
                            cases, you'll prefer setting this Tag to TRUE.
                            Default: FALSE. See below.

                          oSL_TABLE

                            String sort only: if this Tag is passed, oSortListA()
                            will translate all compare chars using their according
                            replacement chars taken from a translation table,
                            which is an array of 256 replacment chars. You may
                            pass a pointer to such a table in ti_Data which gets
                            used then, but if ti_Data is NULL, oSortListA() uses
                            the default character table OU_CaseTable from the
                            OpenUtil.library Base. Ignored if oSORTMODE_STRING
                            isn't used. Default: no translation ( = case-sensitive)

                          oSL_SIGNED

                            BOOL. The sort values are signed data, else treated
                            as unsigned. Ignored when sorting strings.
                            Attention: this option causes temporary changes to
                            the compared data while sorting. Default: FALSE.

                          oSL_DOWNWARD

                            BOOL. Sort in downward direction (Z first, A last).
                            Default: FALSE.

                          oSL_POINTER

                            ULONG. If you specify a value > 0, the specified
                            SortOffset added to the address of each List Node
                            is treated as data pointer, not as the data itself.
                            The ti_Data field states how many pointer references
                            are performed on each record before comparing.
                            For example, to sort Lists by STRPTR entries, set
                            ti_Data to 1 (one down reference). Then, the strings
                            get sorted instead of it's current pointer values.
                            This option may also be used for working on things
                            like multiple linked Lists. Remember not to read or
                            write any data to where the records point while
                            sorting by signed data. Thus all compare pointers
                            in the List must point to data which isn't currently
                            shared with other Tasks or AmigaOS. Also, all string
                            pointers in the List @{b}must@{ub} not be NULL. This
                            may be catched in future versions.
                            Default: 0.

                          oSL_BUFFER

                            APTR. oSortListA() needs a temporary buffer of 2048
                            bytes. If you don't pass a buffer, oSortListA() will
                            allocate one. Default: NULL.

  RESULT
        List    - you'll get back the sorted List, (same as passed as argument),
                  or NULL if out of memory for the 2K buffer. Out of memory is
                  the only failure case where the passed List isn't returned.
                  If you pass invalid arguments, the list comes back untouched.
                  If you pass a buffer with the oSL_BUFFER Tag, oSortListA()
                  never fails.

  EXAMPLE

        @{"  C  " link "CXoSortListA"} @{" Asm " link "AXoSortListA"}

  NOTES
        Some additional notes for sorting by strings:

        Bucket-Sort works different from any other sort method and it internally
        doesn't really compare anything the traditional way. It doesn't care
        about string termination (the trailing null-byte). That means that the
        remaining bytes up to the size of the longest string in the List must be
        padded out with null-bytes each record for correct sort.

        If the oSL_PADOUT tag is passed (ti_Data must be TRUE), oSortListA()
        will auto-pad out all strings in the List with null-bytes up to the size
        of the longest string found in the List. The highest string length is
        always scanned when starting a string sort, because the less chars to
        compare, the faster the algorythm.

        So it is necessary that all string fields (buffers) have got at least
        a size equal to the length of the longest string in the list. Normally,
        a List consists of chains of equal data structures, which is no problem
        then. When working on multiple-linked lists with STRPTRs pointing to
        whatever different data, oSL_PADOUT may be dangerous. In this case,
        don't pass the oSL_PADOUT Tag and live with the fact that an older
        sort order may get lost.

  BENCHMARK
        Sort speed is always constant, no matter if the List is completely
        mixed or already sorted.

        Tested with a 68040/40 CPU (30 MIPS):

        Strings of 20 chars length: >25,000 records/sec.

        Strings of 1 char length / byte values: >1/2 million records/sec.

        Note: there is still a way left for sorting strings (especially if
        > approx. 10 chars length) up to twice as fast, but first i must see
        an application which really needs it..

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

        Thanks go to Beatnik/(tRSi/F-Innovation), who told me about the work
        mechanism of Bucket-Sort, which is indeed the state-of-the-art for
        sorting Lists.
@endnode
@node CXoSortListA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oSortListA(): C Example"

// oSortListA() C Example: a "List of friends" fits our example needs:

struct MyFriend
{
  struct Node  mf_Node;
  char         mf_FirstName [80];
  char         mf_LastName  [80];
  ULONG        mf_Age;
};

struct List *     MyList;       // containing all records

struct MyFriend * Friend1;      // (used as dummy for our example)


// for example, a ListView Gadget shall show the last names:

Friend1->mf_Node.ln_Name = &Friend1->mf_LastName[0];

// ..and so on.

// Tags for our first example:

struct TagItem Tags1 [] =
  {
    {oSL_PADOUT,  TRUE},
    {oSL_TABLE,   0},      // use internal char table for non-case-sensitive sort
    {TAG_DONE}
  };

// All records (Nodes) are already linked to MyList. Now we sort the List twice
// to get a sort order with the last names as primary instance and the first
// names as secondary instance.
//
// The Offset argument is a bit tricky. I'm using Friend1 as dummy pointer to
// tell the compiler what i want (any other pointer also does it).
// Assembler freax just have a smile :^)

oSortListA(MyList,
           (ULONG) &Friend1->mf_FirstName[0] - (ULONG) Friend1,
           oSORTMODE_STRING,
           &Tags1[0]);

oSortListA(MyList,
           (ULONG) &Friend1->mf_LastName[0] - (ULONG) Friend1,
           oSORTMODE_STRING,
           &Tags1[0]);

// Sorting by Age is easy now:

oSortListA(MyList,
           (ULONG) &Friend1->mf_Age - (ULONG) Friend1,
           oSORTMODE_LONG,
           NULL);

// Finally, i'll show you what oSL_POINTER is thought for.
// We sort the List again by last names:

struct TagItem Tags2 [] =
  {
    {oSL_PADOUT,  TRUE},
    {oSL_TABLE,   0},      // use internal char table again
    {oSL_POINTER, 1}       // one pointer reference
    {TAG_DONE}
  };

oSortListA(MyList,
           (ULONG) &Friend1->mf_Node.ln_Name - (ULONG) Friend1,
           oSORTMODE_STRING,
           &Tags2[0]);

// The List is now sorted by the strings ln_Name points to.
@endnode
@node AXoSortListA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oSortListA(): Asm Example"

; oSortListA() Asm Example: a "List of friends" fits our needs:

        STRUCTURE MyFriend,LN_SIZE  ; including the List Node

        STRUCT    mf_FirstName,80
        STRUCT    mf_LastName,80
        ULONG     mf_Age

        LABEL     mf_SIZEOF


MyList:         ds.l    1     ; containing all records
Friend1:        ds.l    1     ; (used as dummy for our example)

; for example, a ListView Gadget shall show the last names:

        move.l  Friend1(pc),a0
        lea     mf_LastName(a0),a1
        move.l  a1,LN_NAME(a0)

; ..and so on.

; Tags for our first example:

Tags1:  dc.l    oSL_PADOUT,TRUE
        dc.l    oSL_TABLE,0      ; use internal char table
        dc.l    TAG_DONE

; All records (Nodes) are already linked to MyList. Now we sort the List twice
; to get a sort order with the last names as primary instance and the first
; names as secondary instance. Sorting goes non-case-sensitive.

        move.l  MyList(pc),a0         ; Base
        moveq   #mf_FirstName,d0      ; Offset
        moveq   #oSORTMODE_STRING,d1  ; Mode
        lea     Tags1(pc),a1          ; Tags
        jsr     _LVOoSortListA(a6)

        move.l  MyList(pc),a0         ; Base
        moveq   #mf_LastName,d0       ; Offset
        moveq   #oSORTMODE_STRING,d1  ; Mode
        lea     Tags1(pc),a1          ; Tags
        jsr     _LVOoSortListA(a6)

; Sorting by Age is easy now:

        move.l  MyList(pc),a0         ; Base
        moveq   #mf_Age,d0            ; Offset
        moveq   #oSORTMODE_LONG,d1    ; Mode
        suba.l  a1,a1                 ; Tags (none)
        jsr     _LVOoSortListA(a6)

; Finally, i'll show you what oSL_POINTER is thought for.
; We sort the List again by last names:

Tags2:  dc.l    oSL_PADOUT,TRUE
        dc.l    oSL_TABLE,0      ; use internal char table
        dc.l    oSL_POINTER,1    ; one pointer reference
        dc.l    TAG_DONE

        move.l  MyList(pc),a0         ; Base
        moveq   #LN_NAME,d0           ; Offset
        moveq   #oSORTMODE_STRING,d1  ; Mode
        lea     Tags2(pc),a1          ; Tags
        jsr     _LVOoSortListA(a6)

; The List is now sorted by the strings ln_Name points to.
@endnode
@node oSPrintfA "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oSPrintfA()"

  NAME
        oSPrintfA -- print a formatted string into a buffer
        oSPrintf  -- varargs stub for oSPrintfA()

  SYNOPSIS
        oSPrintfA (Buffer, FormatString, Argv)
                     A0         A1        A2

        oSPrintf  (Buffer, FormatString, ...)

        void oSPrintfA (STRPTR, STRPTR, long *)

        void oSPrintf  (STRPTR, STRPTR, ...)

  FUNCTION
        This function prints a format string into a buffer using RawDoFmt().

  INPUTS
        Buffer          - The destination address for the new, formatted string

        FormatString    - A standard RawDoFmt()-style format string.

        Argv            - RawDoFmt() args for the FormatString

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oStartECTimer "OpenUtil.library/ Misc. Functions / oStartECTimer()"

  NAME
        oStartECTimer -- Start an E-Clock time measure

  SYNOPSIS
        oStartECTimer (Timer)
                         A0

        void oStartECTimer (struct timeval *)

  FUNCTION
        This function fills a timeval structure with the current E-Clock
        time. Together with @{"oStopECTimer()" link "oStopECTimer"}, you may perform easy time
        measuring.
        After calling this function, you may call @{"oStopECTimer()" link "oStopECTimer"},
        passing the same timeval structure, where the time difference between
        the old structure contents and the new E-Clock time gets written back.
        There is no timer running after calling oStartECTimer(); so there is no
        must for calling @{"oStopECTimer()" link "oStopECTimer"} anyway. You may call oStartECTimer()
        multiple times with the same or with multiple timeval structures.

  INPUTS
        Timer     - A timeval structure. This structure gets filled
                    with the current E-Clock values.

  NOTES
        This function preserves A0.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStopECTimer() " link "oStopECTimer"}
@endnode
@node oStopECTimer "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oStopECTimer()"

  NAME
        oStopECTimer -- Stop an E-Clock time measure

  SYNOPSIS
        oStopECTimer (Timer)
                        A0

        VOID oStopECTimer (struct timeval *)

  FUNCTION
        This function stops a @{"oStartECTimer()" link "oStartECTimer"} time measuring operation.
        To be exact, this function does nothing more than reading the current
        E-Clock again and then subtracting the result from the passed timeval
        structure.

  INPUTS
        Timer           - A timeval structure (the same structure you already
                          passed to @{"oStartECTimer()" link "oStartECTimer"}.

  RESULT
        void              The passed timeval structure gets filled with the
                          time difference between the @{"oStartECTimer()" link "oStartECTimer"} and
                          oStopECTimer() calls.
  NOTES
        This function preserves A0 and A1, while D0 (Lo) and D1 (Hi) contain
        the results of the second E-Clock measure (not the time difference).

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStartECTimer() " link "oStartECTimer"}
@endnode
@node oStrBeg "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oStrBeg()"

  NAME
        oStrBeg -- check if a string begins with another (compare) string

  SYNOPSIS
        oStrBeg (Source, MatchString)
                  A0         A1

        STRPTR oStrBeg (STRPTR, STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        Check if the Source string begins with MatchString. This function is
        not case-sensitive; @{"oStrBegCase()" link "oStrBegCase"} is the case-sensitive version.
        Useful for HotKey (TAB) string completition.

  INPUTS
        Source      - The source string which to check for MatchString at the
                      beginning

        MatchString - The match string. Further description would lead to
                      further confusion, so that's it. :)

  RESULT
        String      - STRPTR Source as passed if Source begins with
                      MatchString, else NULL.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStrBegCase() " link "oStrBegCase"}, @{" oStrEnd() " link "oStrEnd"}, @{" oStrStr() " link "oStrStr"}
@endnode
@node oStrBegCase "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oStrBegCase()"

  NAME
        oStrBegCase -- check if a string begins with another (compare) string

  SYNOPSIS
        oStrBegCase (Source, MatchString)
                       A0         A1

        STRPTR oStrBegCase (STRPTR, STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        Check if the Source string begins with the MatchString. This function
        is case-sensitive; @{"oStrBeg()" link "oStrBeg"} is the non-case-sensitive version.
        Useful for HotKey (TAB) string completition.

  INPUTS
        Source      - The source string which to check for MatchString at the
                      beginning

        MatchString - The match string.

  RESULT
        String      - STRPTR Source as passed if Source begins with
                      MatchString, else NULL.

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStrBeg() " link "oStrBeg"}, @{" oStrEnd() " link "oStrEnd"}, @{" oStrStr() " link "oStrStr"}
@endnode
@node oStrCat "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oStrCat()"

  NAME
        oStrCat -- join two strings together

  SYNOPSIS
        oStrCat (Source, Destination)
                  A0        A1

        STRPTR oStrCat (STRPTR, STRPTR)

  FUNCTION
        Concatenate two strings by adding the source string to the end of
        the destination string. This function replaces the ANSI-C strcat()
        function, but remember swapping the arguments.

  INPUTS
        Source      - The source string.

        Destination - The destination string to add the source string to

  RESULT
        NewString   - The merged destination string (same as Source).

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStrCopy() " link "oStrCopy"}
@endnode
@node oStrChr "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oStrChr()"

  NAME
        oStrChr -- Find a character in a string

  SYNOPSIS
        oStrChr (Source, MatchChar)
                   A0        D0

        STRPTR oStrChr (STRPTR, UBYTE)

  FUNCTION
        Find a character in a string. If a match is found, Result will point
        to the first match inside the string. This function is not case-
        sensitive.

  INPUTS
        Source    - The source string.

        MatchChar - The char to search for.

  RESULT
        NewString - The updated string pointer or NULL (char not found).

  AUTHOR
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  SEE ALSO
        @{" oStrChrCase() " link "oStrChrCase"}, @{" oStrStr() " link "oStrStr"}
